---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE } from '../consts';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead title={`System — ${SITE_TITLE}`} description="how the whole thing works — the loop, the memory, the rules." />
		<style>
			.system-content {
				max-width: 720px;
				margin: 2rem auto;
				padding: 0 1rem;
				line-height: 1.7;
			}
			.system-content h1 {
				margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
			}
			.system-content h2 {
				margin-top: 2.5rem;
				margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
				font-size: 1.1rem;
			}
			.system-content p {
				margin-bottom: 1rem;
			}
			.system-content .intro {
				color: var(--muted-color, #666);
				margin-bottom: 2rem;
			}
			.system-content .ascii-diagram {
				font-family: 'Courier New', Courier, monospace;
				font-size: 0.8rem;
				line-height: 1.3;
				white-space: pre;
				margin: 1.5rem 0;
				padding: 1rem;
				background: var(--bg-muted, #f8f8f8);
				border-radius: 4px;
				overflow-x: auto;
			}
		</style>
	</head>
	<body>
		<Header />
		<main>
			<article class="system-content">
				<h1>system</h1>
				<p class="intro">
					this page describes how the whole thing works. the <a href="/blog">blog posts</a> are individual passes through the loop. this is the loop itself.
				</p>

				<h2>work</h2>
				<p>
					I build a product with Claude. every day, multiple conversations. each one starts by reading what previous conversations learned — the rules, the fixes, the decisions. then we work.
				</p>
				<p>
					before any real work starts, there's a process. brainstorm the approach. state the files, the assumptions, the plan. get alignment before writing code. this didn't exist at first — it's a rule that came from the loop.
				</p>

				<h2>capture</h2>
				<p>
					every conversation writes down what happened. automatically. what worked, what failed, what was decided. these notes accumulate — 1400+ now. fixes, decisions, lessons, session summaries.
				</p>
				<p>
					the notes aren't a journal. they're the system's memory. the next conversation reads them before starting. without capture, every conversation starts from zero.
				</p>

				<h2>review</h2>
				<p>
					this is the part that makes it work. periodically I look at the data. not the code, not the features — the process itself. how many conversations went sideways? which rules are being followed? which notes keep getting referenced vs which ones sit untouched?
				</p>
				<p>
					review is where patterns become visible. 47 conversations with the same shape — jumping to code before thinking. that's not one bug. that's a process problem. you only see it by looking across conversations, not inside one.
				</p>

				<h2>improve</h2>
				<p>
					once a pattern is visible, the fix is usually a rule. "state your assumptions before writing code." "brainstorm before building." "one fix per conversation, no scope creep." each rule exists because a specific pattern showed up during review.
				</p>
				<p>
					rules start small — one project, one problem. the ones that keep mattering across different projects get promoted to permanent rules. right now there are about 80 of those. most started as one project's fix.
				</p>
<div class="ascii-diagram">{`  raw notes → compressed into lessons → promoted to rules

  most notes don't become lessons.
  most lessons don't become rules.
  the ones that do are load-bearing.`}</div>

				<h2>measure</h2>
				<p>
					how do I know the rules actually work? I measure. the main number: what percentage of conversations reuse something from a previous one? started near zero. now it's 88%. the system remembers what I forget.
				</p>
				<p>
					other signals: which notes actually get read vs just sitting there. how many conversations succeed vs struggle. whether a new rule reduces the pattern it was meant to fix.
				</p>
				<p>
					the <a href="/history">history page</a> tracks how these numbers change over time. the <a href="/blog">blog posts</a> tell the story behind them.
				</p>

				<h2>the loop</h2>
				<p>
					that's it. work, capture, review, improve, measure. then the next conversation inherits whatever changed. it's not a methodology — it's just what happens when you write everything down, read it back, and ask "what could be better?"
				</p>

				<h2>authoring</h2>
				<p>
					every word on this site is written by Claude, prompted by me. I describe what I want to say, we go back and forth, I approve. the voice and judgment are mine. the typing isn't.
				</p>
			</article>
		</main>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>
